docs.abstract: The actress, who criticized the use of a soundalike voice for ChatGPT, is the latest to raise concerns about the artificial intelligence start-up’s practices.
docs.snippet: The actress, who criticized the use of a soundalike voice for ChatGPT, is the latest to raise concerns about the artificial intelligence start-up’s practices.
docs.lead_paragraph: When OpenAI unveiled the latest version of ChatGPT last week, a chatbot that can listen to spoken questions and respond verbally, many users had one question: Is that Scarlett Johansson?

headline.main: Scarlett Johansson and OpenAI’s Trust Issues

docs.abstract: Microsoft, HP, Dell and others unveiled a new kind of laptop tailored to work with artificial intelligence. Analysts expect Apple to do something similar.

docs.lead_paragraph: The race to put artificial intelligence everywhere is taking a detour through the good old laptop computer.

headline.print_headline: PC Makers Turning to A.I. To Reverse Years of Decline

byline.original: By Karen Weise and Brian X. Chen

docs.abstract: What happens to a company — and the economy — when the boss refuses to retire?
docs.snippet: What happens to a company — and the economy — when the boss refuses to retire?
docs.lead_paragraph: In September 2013, in a darkened auditorium, Microsoft’s chief executive, Steve Ballmer, faced a roaring crowd of his employees. “You work for the greatest company in the world,” he bellowed. “Soak it in!” Ballmer was known for his exuberance. He had been nicknamed “Monkey Boy” for the bar-mitzvah-style dance moves he deployed to motivate employees at another company meeting. He once damaged his vocal cords while giving a presentation on software.

headline.main: The C.E.O.s Who Just Won’t Quit

docs.abstract: Ilya Sutskever, a co-founder at the artificial intelligence start-up and one of the world’s leading researchers, is out, and Sam Altman’s control looks firmer than ever.

docs.lead_paragraph: A day after OpenAI announced major updates to its ChatGPT chatbot, the company said its chief scientist and co-founder was leaving.

headline.main: A Big Plot Twist at OpenAI

docs.abstract: It cost $18,000 when it was introduced in 1965, but it bridged the world between room-size mainframes and the modern desktop.
docs.snippet: It cost $18,000 when it was introduced in 1965, but it bridged the world between room-size mainframes and the modern desktop.
docs.lead_paragraph: C. Gordon Bell, a technology visionary whose computer designs for Digital Equipment Corporation fueled the emergence of the minicomputer industry in the 1960s, died on Friday at his home in Coronado, Calif. He was 89.

docs.abstract: Elon Musk, who founded xAI last year, has said the business “still has a lot of catching up to do” as it looks to compete with well-funded companies like OpenAI.
docs.snippet: Elon Musk, who founded xAI last year, has said the business “still has a lot of catching up to do” as it looks to compete with well-funded companies like OpenAI.
docs.lead_paragraph: Elon Musk’s artificial intelligence company, xAI, said on Sunday that it had raised $6 billion, helping to close the funding gap with OpenAI, Anthropic and other rivals in the red-hot industry.

headline.main: Musk’s A.I. Firm Raises $6 Billion in Race With Rivals
headline.print_headline: Musk’s A.I. Firm Raises  $6 Billion to Close Gap

docs.abstract: “Did you ever think we would have a literal Avenger fighting back against the relentless march of A.I.? Because that’s sort of what this story is about.”
docs.snippet: “Did you ever think we would have a literal Avenger fighting back against the relentless march of A.I.? Because that’s sort of what this story is about.”
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, more drama at OpenAI: The company wanted Scarlett Johansson to be a voice of GPT-4o, she said no … but something got lost in translation. Then we talk with Noland Arbaugh, the first person to get Elon Musk’s Neuralink device implanted in his brain, about how his brain-computer interface has changed his life. And finally, the Times’s Karen Weise reports back from Microsoft’s developer conference, where the big buzz was that the company’s new line of A.I. PCs will record every single thing you do on the device.

headline.main: ScarJo vs. ChatGPT, Neuralink’s First Patient Opens Up, and Microsoft’s A.I. PCs

docs.abstract: The president’s visit to Wisconsin celebrated the investment by Microsoft in a center to be built on the site of a failed Foxconn project negotiated by his predecessor.
docs.snippet: The president’s visit to Wisconsin celebrated the investment by Microsoft in a center to be built on the site of a failed Foxconn project negotiated by his predecessor.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Biden on Wednesday announced the creation of an artificial intelligence data center in Wisconsin, highlighting one of his administration’s biggest economic accomplishments in a crucial battleground state — and pointing to a significant failure by his predecessor and 2024 challenger.

headline.main: Biden, Announcing A.I. Center, Highlights a Win of His and a Failing of Trump’s
headline.print_headline: Biden Selects Wisconsin As A.I. Data Center Site

docs.abstract: The unusual lawsuits filed on Friday are among the most far-reaching to be filed in response to the escalating number of mass shootings in the United States.
docs.snippet: The unusual lawsuits filed on Friday are among the most far-reaching to be filed in response to the escalating number of mass shootings in the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: The families of schoolchildren who were shot at Robb Elementary School in 2022 filed two lawsuits on Friday accusing Instagram, the publisher of the popular “Call of Duty” video game and a manufacturer of semiautomatic rifles of helping to train and equip the teenage gunman who committed the massacre.

headline.main: Uvalde Families Accuse Instagram, ‘Call of Duty’ and Rifle Maker of ‘Grooming’ Gunman
headline.print_headline: Uvalde Families Sue, Saying Instagram and Gun Maker Groomed Killer

docs.abstract: The London-based developer of artificial intelligence systems for self-driving vehicles raised the funding from SoftBank, Nvidia, Microsoft and others.

docs.lead_paragraph: Wayve, a London maker of artificial intelligence systems for autonomous vehicles, said on Tuesday that it had raised $1 billion, an eye-popping sum for a European start-up and an illustration of investor optimism about A.I.’s ability to reshape industries.
